 Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"GARLANDE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>gerlond</i>, <i>ger(e)land</i>, <i>garlond</i> ‘metal chaplet, crown, coronet; wreath’, probably a nickname denoting a habitual wearer of such items, or a metonymic occupational name for a maker of them.","English: perhaps from the Old French personal name <i>Gerland</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Garuland</i>, probably from <i>garw-</i> ‘war-gear; prepared(ness)’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’; the first element of the French name may instead be from a name beginning with <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’).","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>lond</i> ‘land’ (Old English <i>gāra</i> + <i>land</i>, <i>lond</i>), for someone who lived ‘(at the) triangular piece of land’. Compare   Garfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerland","meanings":["English (North Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Garland  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Garfield","meanings":["English (Midlands): topographic name from Middle English <i>gor(e)</i>, <i>gar(e)</i> ‘triangular piece’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country, field’ (Old English <i>gār</i> + <i>feld</i>), for someone who lived by a triangular piece of land.","English: alternatively, sometimes perhaps a variant of   Carville   (a name of Norman origin), with excrescent final <i>-d</i>.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Gartland","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Garland  .","Irish (northern Leinster and southern Ulster): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Mac Gearnúin</b>, a patronymic from the Norman personal name   Gernon  ."]}]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Marie DE GARLANDE was born about 1200, in Livry-sur-Vesle, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France, her father, Guillaume DE GARLANDE V, was 42 and her mother, Adèle DE CHÂTILLON-SUR-MARNE, was 36. She married Comte Henri IV de Grandpre after 1204. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1259."},"et":{"environ 1200–après 1259":"umbes 1200–pärast 1259","1200–1259":"1200–1259","1191–1231":"1191–1231","1195–1245":"1195–1245","1211–1287":"1211–1287","1220–1269":"1220–1269","1160–1216":"1160–1216","1165–1216":"1165–1216","14 août 1231":"14. august 1231","environ 1200":"umbes 1200","AFT 1204":"pärast 1204","1165":"1165","1220":"1220","1231":"1231","1195":"1195","1193":"1193","1160":"1160","1191":"1191","après 1259":"pärast 1259","1216":"1216","1259":"1259","1269":"1269","1245":"1245","1211":"1211","1200":"1200","1287":"1287","about 1220":"umbes 1220","après 1216":"pärast 1216","Livry-sur-Vesle, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France":"Livry-sur-Vesle, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, Prantsusmaa","Montréal, Yonne, Burgundy, France":"Montréal, Yonne, Bourgogne, Prantsusmaa","france":"Prantsusmaa","Lorraine, France":"Lorraine, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"environ 1200–après 1259":"noin 1200–1259 jälkeen","1200–1259":"1200–1259","1191–1231":"1191–1231","1195–1245":"1195–124